                <h2>What Types of Divorce Cases Does a Divorce Lawyer in Karachi Handle?</h2>

                <p>MR Law Associates handles every form of marital dissolution recognised under Pakistani law. Each type
                    has its own procedure, timeline, and financial consequences for both spouses, so the first thing we
                    do is help you understand which route actually fits your situation.</p>

                <div class="service-features">
                    <div class="feature-box reveal">
                        <h3>Khula (Wife-Initiated Divorce)</h3>
                        <p>Filing <strong>khula petitions before the Family Court</strong> under Section 10(4) of the
                            Family Courts Act. The wife seeks dissolution by offering to return her dower. The husband's
                            consent isn't required after the 2015 amendment. Courts grant khula once satisfied that the
                            wife cannot live within the limits ordained by Allah, and we handle the whole
                            <a href="/services/khula-procedure/" style="color:var(--accent-gold-dark);">khula procedure</a>
                            for you.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-box reveal">
                        <h3>Talaq (Husband-Initiated Divorce)</h3>
                        <p>Assisting with <strong>proper talaq procedures</strong> under Section 7 of the Muslim Family
                            Laws Ordinance 1961. The husband must send written notice to the Union Council Chairman and
                            to the wife. A 90-day reconciliation period follows. If reconciliation fails, the divorce
                            becomes effective on the 91st day, and we make sure the notice is valid so it can't be
                            challenged later.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-box reveal">
                        <h3>Judicial Divorce (Dissolution of Marriage)</h3>
                        <p>Filing for <strong>court-ordered divorce on specific grounds</strong> under the Dissolution
