                            to maintain (2 years), imprisonment (7 or more years), impotence, insanity, and cruelty. The
                            court grants the divorce once it verifies the ground you've claimed.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-box reveal">
                        <h3>Custody & Visitation</h3>
                        <p>Handling <strong>child custody disputes during and after divorce</strong>. Under Islamic law,
                            mothers keep custody (hizanat) for boys until age 7 and girls until puberty, and courts put
                            the child's welfare first. We negotiate
                            <a href="/services/child-custody-lawyer/" style="color:var(--accent-gold-dark);">custody arrangements</a>
                            and secure visitation rights for the non-custodial parent.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h2>How Does the Khula Process Work in Karachi?</h2>

                <p>Khula is the most common form of wife-initiated divorce in Karachi's Family Courts. The process runs
                    through filing a suit, a mandatory reconciliation attempt, and a court decree that dissolves the
                    marriage. Under the 2015 amendment the husband's consent is no longer needed, which means a woman is
                    no longer trapped simply because her husband refuses to let go.</p>

                <ol style="color:var(--text-secondary); padding-left:1.5rem; line-height:2.2;">
                    <li><strong>Legal consultation:</strong> Your divorce lawyer listens to your situation, identifies
                        the applicable grounds, and explains the financial picture (dower return, maintenance,
                        property) in plain language.</li>
                    <li><strong>Suit filing:</strong> A khula petition is filed in the Family Court that has
                        jurisdiction over where the wife currently lives or where the marriage took place. The petition
                        sets out the grounds for dissolution and the dower details.</li>
                    <li><strong>Court summons:</strong> The court issues notice to the husband to appear and respond,
                        usually within 30 days.</li>
                    <li><strong>Reconciliation attempt:</strong> The court holds a reconciliation hearing where both
                        parties, and often their families, try to resolve differences. If reconciliation fails, the case
                        moves ahead.</li>
                    <li><strong>Evidence and arguments:</strong> Both sides present their case. The wife explains why she
                        cannot continue the marriage, and the husband may contest or negotiate terms.</li>
                    <li><strong>Decree:</strong> The court grants a khula decree once satisfied. The decree records the
                        dower position, custody arrangements, and maintenance obligations.</li>
                    <li><strong>Iddat period:</strong> The wife observes iddat (3 menstrual cycles or 3 months) and
                        cannot remarry during this time.</li>
                </ol>

                <h2>Khula vs Talaq: What Is the Difference?</h2>

                <p>Khula and talaq are the two primary routes to divorce in Pakistan, started by different spouses with
                    different procedures and financial results. Understanding the distinction helps you choose the right
                    legal path, and it's one of the first things we walk you through.</p>

