                <h2>What Are the Legal Grounds for Divorce in Pakistan?</h2>

                <p>The Dissolution of Muslim Marriages Act 1939 lists specific grounds on which a wife can seek judicial
                    divorce. These grounds are separate from khula and don't require the wife to return her dower. The
                    court dissolves the marriage once the claimed ground is proven.</p>

                <ul style="color:var(--text-secondary); padding-left:1.5rem; line-height:2;">
                    <li><strong>Husband missing for 4+ years:</strong> Whereabouts unknown and no maintenance provided.
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Failure to maintain for 2+ years:</strong> The husband hasn't provided financial support
                        without a valid reason.</li>
                    <li><strong>Imprisonment for 7+ years:</strong> The husband has been sentenced to imprisonment of 7
                        years or more.</li>
                    <li><strong>Impotence:</strong> The husband is impotent and the condition existed at the time of
                        marriage.</li>
                    <li><strong>Insanity for 2+ years:</strong> The husband has been of unsound mind for at least 2
                        years.</li>
                    <li><strong>Cruelty:</strong> Physical violence, mental torture, forcing you into immoral conduct,
                        disposing of your property, obstructing your religious practice, or unequal treatment among
                        multiple wives.</li>
                    <li><strong>Option of puberty:</strong> If a girl was married before age 16 by a guardian other than
                        the father, she can repudiate the marriage before age 18.</li>
                    <li><strong>Any other ground recognised under Islamic law:</strong> Courts have discretion to
                        recognise additional grounds based on Sharia principles.</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>What Happens to Children After Divorce in Karachi?</h2>

                <p>Child custody after divorce follows the welfare-of-the-child principle, supported by Islamic law
                    guidelines on hizanat. Courts design arrangements that serve the child's best interests, and that
                    often means shared elements and guaranteed visitation rather than shutting one parent out.</p>

                <ul style="color:var(--text-secondary); padding-left:1.5rem; line-height:2;">
                    <li><strong>Mother's preference:</strong> Under Islamic law, mothers have preferential custody for
                        boys until age 7 and girls until puberty. That's the starting point, not the final word.</li>
                    <li><strong>Father's financial obligation:</strong> Whoever has custody, the father stays
                        financially responsible for the children's food, education, healthcare, and clothing.</li>
                    <li><strong>Visitation rights:</strong> The non-custodial parent receives court-ordered visitation,
                        commonly alternate weekends, part of school holidays, and shared religious celebrations.</li>
                    <li><strong>Guardian assessment:</strong> In a contested custody dispute, the court may look closely
                        at both parents' homes before deciding the arrangement that serves the child's welfare.</li>
                    <li><strong>Child's preference:</strong> A child old enough to express a view is heard by the court,
                        though the wish isn't automatically binding.</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Divorce, Domestic Violence and Your Protection</h2>

                <p>For many women, the hardest part isn't the paperwork, it's the fear of what an angry husband might do.
                    You don't have to stay in danger while your case is pending. Alongside a divorce or khula suit, the
                    court can pass protection and residence orders so an abusive husband can't harass you, hurt you, or
                    throw you out of the home. If you've faced beating, threats, or emotional abuse, please keep any
                    medical reports, messages, photos, or witness details, because that evidence helps us secure faster
                    protection for you and your children. This is confidential, and a female advocate handles it with
                    the care it deserves.</p>

                <h2>Maintenance, Dower and Financial Support After Divorce</h2>

                <p>Divorce isn't only about ending a marriage, it's about making sure you and your children aren't left
                    without support. We pursue the financial claims that Pakistani law gives you, so you can rebuild with
                    some stability.</p>

                <ul style="color:var(--text-secondary); padding-left:1.5rem; line-height:2;">
                    <li><strong>Iddat maintenance:</strong> The husband must maintain the wife during the iddat period,
                        covering housing, food, clothing, and medical costs at the standard she was used to.</li>
                    <li><strong>Child maintenance:</strong> We claim regular monthly
                        <a href="/services/maintenance-alimony-lawyer/" style="color:var(--accent-gold-dark);">maintenance and alimony</a>
                        for your children, with the amount tied to the father's means and the children's needs.</li>
                    <li><strong>Dower (haq mehr) recovery:</strong> Any unpaid deferred dower can be recovered through
                        the court. Our <a href="/services/dower-haq-mehr-recovery/" style="color:var(--accent-gold-dark);">dower recovery</a>
                        work makes sure a woman gets what she's owed.</li>
                    <li><strong>Dowry articles:</strong> The jahez and personal belongings you brought into the marriage
                        can be recovered through a <a href="/services/dowry-articles-recovery/" style="color:var(--accent-gold-dark);">dowry articles recovery</a>
                        claim.</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Family Courts and Jurisdiction in Divorce Cases</h2>

                <p>Divorce and khula suits are decided by the Family Courts, and the right court usually depends on where
                    the wife currently resides. Getting jurisdiction correct matters, because a case filed in the wrong
                    court wastes precious months. We file in the proper court from the start and handle every hearing, so
                    you're not running from counter to counter on your own. If the other spouse ignores a maintenance or
                    custody order after the decree, we move quickly to enforcement, filing execution proceedings so the
                    order is actually obeyed and not just written on paper.</p>

                <h2>What Documents Do You Need to File for Divorce or Khula in Karachi?</h2>

                <p>Walking into court prepared saves you weeks of delay, so I always give clients a simple checklist at
                    our first meeting. You don't need every paper on day one, and if something's missing or lost, we work
                    around it. Here's what usually helps your divorce or khula case move faster.</p>

                <ul style="color:var(--text-secondary); padding-left:1.5rem; line-height:2;">
                    <li><strong>Nikah nama (marriage certificate):</strong> The registered marriage contract. If you
                        can't find your copy, the Union Council that recorded the nikah can issue a certified one.</li>
                    <li><strong>CNIC copies:</strong> Your national identity card, and the husband's if you have it.</li>
                    <li><strong>Children's documents:</strong> B-forms or birth certificates, since custody and
                        maintenance for the children are decided alongside the divorce.</li>
                    <li><strong>Dower proof:</strong> Anything showing the agreed haq mehr and whether it was paid, which
                        matters for both khula and dower recovery.</li>
                    <li><strong>Evidence of the ground:</strong> For a judicial divorce, papers that support your claim,
                        such as medical reports for cruelty, or proof the husband hasn't maintained you.</li>
                    <li><strong>Contact details:</strong> The husband's current address so the court can serve notice
                        without months of delay.</li>
                </ul>

                <p>Don't worry if your file is incomplete. Part of our job is helping you gather or reconstruct what the
                    court needs, and we never turn a woman away because a paper's gone missing.</p>

                <h2>Guardianship and the Guardian Courts in Karachi</h2>

                <p>People often mix up custody and guardianship, and the difference genuinely matters. Custody (hizanat)
                    is about who the child lives with day to day. Guardianship is about who holds legal authority over the
                    child's property and major decisions, and it's dealt with under the Guardians and Wards Act 1890,
                    usually before the Guardian Court. A mother can keep custody while the father stays the natural
                    guardian, and there are times a mother needs a formal
                    <a href="/services/guardianship-certificate-lawyer/" style="color:var(--accent-gold-dark);">guardianship certificate</a>
                    to act for her child, whether that's for a passport, a bank account, or an inheritance. If your
                    divorce touches any of this, we handle the guardianship side too, so nothing falls through the
                    cracks.</p>

                <h2>Property and Financial Rights After Divorce in Pakistan</h2>

                <p>A worry I hear often is whether a woman loses everything when a marriage ends. Under Pakistani law
                    there's no automatic 50-50 split of the husband's property the way some other countries do, but that
                    doesn't mean you walk away with nothing. What's legally yours stays yours, and we make sure you claim
                    it in full.</p>

                <ul style="color:var(--text-secondary); padding-left:1.5rem; line-height:2;">
                    <li><strong>Your own property:</strong> Anything in your name, your savings, your gold, and gifts made
                        to you stay yours after divorce.</li>
                    <li><strong>Dower (haq mehr):</strong> Unpaid deferred dower is a debt the husband owes you, and the
                        court can order him to pay it.</li>
                    <li><strong>Dowry articles (jahez):</strong> The belongings you brought into the marriage can be
                        recovered, so they aren't kept back out of spite.</li>
                    <li><strong>Maintenance:</strong> Support during iddat for you, and ongoing maintenance for your
                        children, tied to the father's means.</li>
                    <li><strong>The family home:</strong> If you fear being thrown out, a residence order can protect your
                        right to stay while matters are settled.</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Help for Overseas Pakistanis Seeking Divorce in Karachi</h2>

                <p>Plenty of our clients live abroad, in the Gulf, the UK, or the United States, and can't fly back to
                    sit through hearings. You don't have to. Through a special power of attorney, we represent you in the
                    Karachi Family Courts while you stay where you are, and we keep you updated at every step. Your first
                    consultation can happen over a call or a video meeting, whatever feels comfortable, so distance never
                    stops a woman from getting the divorce or khula she needs.</p>

                <h2>Mediation, Reconciliation and Settlement</h2>

                <p>Not every divorce has to be a war. Where there's room, we explore reconciliation and court-approved
                    settlement, because a dignified agreement on custody, maintenance, and dower is often kinder to
                    children than years of bitter litigation. That said, if the other side won't be reasonable or if
                    there's abuse involved, we don't hesitate to fight your case firmly in court. You decide the goal,
                    and we give you honest guidance on what's realistic.</p>

