                <h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid in a Divorce or Khula Case</h2>

                <p>Over the years I've watched avoidable errors cost women time, money, and peace of mind. A little
                    guidance early on saves a great deal of heartache later, so here are the slips we help you sidestep.</p>

                <ul style="color:var(--text-secondary); padding-left:1.5rem; line-height:2;">
                    <li><strong>Filing in the wrong court:</strong> A suit lodged where the court has no jurisdiction can
                        be dismissed, and you're back to square one. We get this right the first time.</li>
                    <li><strong>Giving up dower without advice:</strong> Some women forfeit their haq mehr under pressure
                        when the law might have let them keep it. Talk to a lawyer before you agree to anything.</li>
                    <li><strong>Ignoring maintenance for the children:</strong> Ending the marriage quickly feels urgent,
                        but don't sign away your children's right to support just to get it over with.</li>
                    <li><strong>Not keeping evidence:</strong> Messages, medical reports, and photos matter. Deleting them
                        weakens a cruelty or protection claim.</li>
                    <li><strong>Facing an abusive spouse alone:</strong> If you feel unsafe, ask the court for protection
                        early. You don't have to wait until the divorce is final.</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>After the Divorce: Iddat, Remarriage and Moving Forward</h2>

                <p>Once the decree is granted, a woman observes iddat, roughly three menstrual cycles or three months,
                    and can't remarry during that window. After iddat ends, you're free to remarry if you choose. We also
                    help you collect the certified divorce or khula decree, update your records, and register the decree
                    with the Union Council so there's no confusion about your status later. Closing this chapter properly
                    matters, and we make sure the paperwork protects you down the road.</p>

