                    <div class="feature-box reveal">
                        <h3>How long does a divorce case take in Karachi?</h3>
                        <p>Contested khula: <strong>6 to 18 months</strong>. Uncontested khula with dower return:
                            <strong>3 to 6 months</strong>. Talaq: <strong>90 days</strong> from the Union Council
                            notice. Custody disputes joined to a divorce extend the timeline.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-box reveal">
                        <h3>Does a wife lose her dower in khula?</h3>
                        <p>Usually the wife <strong>returns or forfeits her dower</strong>. But if the husband is at
                            fault through violence, desertion, or failure to maintain, the court may grant khula
                            <strong>without full dower return</strong>. The 2015 amendment strengthened this discretion.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-box reveal">
                        <h3>What are the grounds for divorce under Pakistani law?</h3>
                        <p>Under the <strong>Dissolution of Muslim Marriages Act 1939</strong>, grounds include the
                            husband missing for 4 years, failure to maintain for 2 years, imprisonment for 7 or more
                            years, impotence, insanity, and cruelty. <strong>Khula</strong> needs no specific fault
                            ground.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-box reveal">
                        <h3>Can the court protect me from domestic violence?</h3>
